    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`nvim_exec_lua` accepts args, but `nvim_exec2()` does not. AFAIK, this means there's no ergonomic way to pass args to Vimscript (except `nvim_call_function()`?). \n\nA use-case is updating buffer-local variables without a serialization roundtrip. Currently that requires building a Vimscript string:\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_buf_call(buf, function()\n  vim.cmd(('let b:foo.d.a = %d'):format(a))\n  vim.cmd(('let b:foo.d.b = %d'):format(b))\nend)\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n- `nvim_exec2` could accept an args list similar to `nvim_exec_lua`, then callers can pass values in a readable and performant way. \n    - This may require introducing a `v:args` special global.\n- `nvim_exec2` result includes a `result` field\n\n```lua\nlocal r = vim.api.nvim_exec2(([[\n  let b:foo.d.a = v:args[0]\n  let b:foo.d.b = v:args[1]\n]], {}, { a, b })\n\nvim.print(r.result)\n```\n\n### Bonus\n\nWould this eliminate the need for:\n\n- `nvim_call_function` \n- `nvim_call_dict_function`",
